There has been a threat of violence in the cities of Limbe and Garoua in Cameroon as rebels step up their activity to disrupt AFCON in the troubled Central African country, bringing new warnings of violence against fans and players. With the players already arriving in Cameroon for the one-month delayed tournament. The UK government is advising against all but essential travel to two of the AFCON host cities, Limbe and Garoua, where 12 Premier League players are due to play, including Salah, Manchester United starlet, Hannibal Mejbri and Arsenal ‘s Omar Rekik and Mohamed Elneny.   Egypt also fears  Nigeria  says Musa     Senegal, Egypt are threats to Eagles , Olayinka admits     Amuneke, Okoye differ on  ‘fantastic’ Salah   Read Also: 2021 AFCON: Super Eagles may lose  Ighalo There is also the possibility of attacks across the country, warn human rights groups. Even the British High Commission in the capital, Yaoundé, has been threatened. - Advertisement - But Garoua in the north and Limbe in the west of Cameroon, are considered by the UK government to be particular risks. Garoua will host Group D matches between Egypt, Sudan, Nigeria and Guinea Bissau. A host of Premier League stars will play at the Roumdé-Adjia Stadium. As well as Salah, Egypt’s squad includes, Arsenal’s Mohamed Elneny and Trezeguet.